04118nam a22005655i 9780773588486DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735884867 a10.1515/97807735884862doi  a(DE-B1597)656121  a(OCoLC)1320924961  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBF697.5.S65bC64 2013 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a302.5/42231 aCohen-Gewerc, Elie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSerious Leisure and Individuality /cElie Cohen-Gewerc, Robert A. Stebbins. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (160 p.) :bI figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tFreedom and Being Free -- tLeisure Space: Cradle of the Individuated Person -- tInclination to Play -- tLeisure and Consumption -- tArt in the Leisure Era -- tCommunity, Citizenship, and Globalization -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat does it mean to be an individual and how can an individual exist within society? Serious Leisure and Individuality examines the circumstances in the modern world that make for individual distinctiveness, and the role of these conditions in personal and social life. "The individual," said Friedrich Nietzsche, "has always had to struggle to keep from being overwhelmed by the tribe. If you try it, you will be lonely often, and sometimes frightened. But no price is too high to pay for the privilege of owning yourself." Elie Cohen-Gewerc and Robert Stebbins explore the road to finding that privilege. They approach individuality by examining its relationship to freedom and being free, and by defining and elaborating on the concept of leisure space. They also look at individuality's place in community, citizenship, and globalization. The complex relationship between individuality and alienation is put under the microscope to highlight the negative side of being distinctive, which has adverse consequences for the individual and society. There are many studies on the modern individual that centre almost entirely on the person facing his local community and broader society. What is missing in the literature - and what Serious Leisure and Individuality provides - is a broad, comprehensive examination of individuality, particularly as it is rooted in leisure and the leisure-like areas of work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndividuality -- Social aspects. 0aIndividualityxSocial aspects. 0aPsychology -- Social aspects. 0aPsychologyxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aStebbins, Robert A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358848640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773588486423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773588486/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles